value.value: The process of covalently linking peptidoglycan (murein) to proteins.
The phosphorylation of peptidyl-serine to form peptidyl-O-phospho-L-serine.

The phosphorylation of peptidyl-histidine to form peptidyl-1'-phospho-L-histidine (otherwise known as tau-phosphohistidine, tele-phosphohistidine) or peptidyl-3'-phospho-L-histidine (otherwise known as pi-phosphohistidine, pros-phosphohistidine).
The phosphorylation of peptidyl-threonine to form peptidyl-O-phospho-L-threonine.
The phosphorylation of peptidyl-tyrosine to form peptidyl-O4'-phospho-L-tyrosine.
The phosphorylation of peptidyl-arginine to form omega-N-phospho-L-arginine.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-methionine = D-methionine.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-proline = D-proline.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-lysine = D-lysine.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-threonine = D-threonine.
The addition of an adenylyl group (adenosine 5'-monophosphate; AMP) to a protein amino acid.
The covalent addition of a nitric oxide (NO) group to the sulphur (S) atom of a cysteine residue in a protein, to form peptidyl-S-nitrosyl-L-cysteine.
The methylation of peptidyl-cysteine to form peptidyl-S-methyl-L-cysteine.
The addition of a hydroxy group to a protein amino acid.
Catalysis of the reduction of a peptide-linked oxazoline to oxazole.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of oxazole or thiazole, five-membered heterocyclic ring structures containing an oxygen and a sulfur, respectively, in the 1-position and a nitrogen in the 3-position.
Catalysis of the reduction of a peptide-linked thiazoline to thiazole.
The formation of a covalent cross-link between a nucleic acid and a protein.
The formation of a covalent cross-link between RNA and a protein.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of keratan sulfate, a glycosaminoglycan with repeat units consisting of beta-1,4-linked D-galactopyranosyl-beta-(1,4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine 6-sulfate and with variable amounts of fucose, sialic acid and mannose units; keratan sulfate chains are covalently linked by a glycosidic attachment through the trisaccharide galactosyl-galactosyl-xylose to peptidyl-threonine or serine residues.
The formation of a covalent cross-link between or within protein chains.
The formation of an isopeptide cross-link between peptidyl-lysine and peptidyl-glutamine to produce N6-(L-isoglutamyl)-L-lysine.
The modification of a protein amino acid by oxidation.
The covalent binding of a pyrromethane (dipyrrin) cofactor to protein via the sulfur atom of cysteine forming dipyrrolylmethanemethyl-L-cysteine.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of dipyrrins (pyrromethanes), compounds containing two pyrrole rings linked through a methine, -CH=, group.
Catalysis of the posttranslational transfer of one or more glutamic acid residues to the C-terminus of ribosomal protein S6.
The oxidation of peptidyl-cysteine to peptidyl-L-cysteine sulfinic acid or peptidyl-L-cysteine sulfenic acid.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of peptidyl-1-thioglycine from other compounds, including peptidyl-glycine.
The linkage of protein to heme P460.
The addition of a nucleotide to a protein amino acid.
The addition of phospho-uridine to a protein amino acid.
The modification of a protein amino acid by polyamination.
The covalent linkage of heme to peroxidase.
The modification of peptidyl-proline to form trans-2,3-cis-3,4-dihydroxy-L-proline.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of the cofactor pyrroloquinoline quinone (PQQ); it is synthesized from a small peptide containing tyrosine and glutamic acid; these amino acids in the peptide are multiply cross-linked and the rest of the peptide is removed.
The modification of a protein amino acid by formation of an ester or amide with octanoic acid.
The octanoylation of peptidyl-serine to form peptidyl-O3-octanoyl-L-serine, typical of the protein ghrelin.
The alteration of an amino acid residue in a peptide.
The modification of peptidyl-alanine.
The modification of peptidyl-arginine.
The modification of peptidyl-aspartic acid.
The modification of peptidyl-cysteine.
The modification of peptidyl-glutamine.
The modification of peptidyl-glutamic acid.
The modification of peptidyl-glycine.
The modification of peptidyl-histidine.
The modification of peptidyl-isoleucine.
The modification of peptidyl-leucine.
The modification of peptidyl-lysine.
The modification of peptidyl-methionine.
